04456nam a22005535i 9780226319582DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20162016ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802263195827 a10.7208/97802263195822doi  a(DE-B1597)523728  a(OCoLC)944445011  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aML503.2 7aMUS0000002bisacsh04a784.0945/090322231 aCypess, Rebecca, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCurious and Modern Inventions :bInstrumental Music as Discovery in Galileo's Italy /cRebecca Cypess. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2016] 4cÂ©2016  a1 online resource (320 p.) :b4 color plates, 17 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tList of Tables -- tAcknowledgments -- tEditorial Principles -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1 The Paradox of Instrumentality The Material and the Ephemeral in Early Modern Instrumental Music -- tChapter 2 Instruments of the Affetti Biagio Marini's Affetti musicali (1617) -- tChapter 3 Portraiture in Motion Instrumental Music and the Representation of the Affetti -- tChapter 4 "Curiose e moderne inventioni" Biagio Marini's Sonate (1626) and Carlo Farina's "Capriccio stravagante" (1627) as Collections of Curiosities -- tChapter 5 Instruments of Timekeeping The Case of Frescobaldi's Toccate e partite . . . libro primo -- tChapter 6 The stile moderno and the Art of History Artisanship and Historical Consciousness in the Works of Dario Castello -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tMusical Works Cited -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEarly seventeenth-century Italy saw a revolution in instrumental music. Large, varied, and experimental, the new instrumental repertoire was crucial for the Western tradition-but until now, the impulses that gave rise to it had yet to be fully explored. Curious and Modern Inventions offers fresh insight into the motivating forces behind this music, tracing it to a new conception of instruments of all sorts-whether musical, artistic, or scientific-as vehicles of discovery. Rebecca Cypess shows that early modern thinkers were fascinated with instrumental technologies. The telescope, the clock, the pen, the lute-these were vital instruments for leading thinkers of the age, from Galileo Galilei to Giambattista Marino. No longer used merely to remake an object or repeat a process already known, instruments were increasingly seen as tools for open-ended inquiry that would lead to new knowledge. Engaging with themes from the history of science, literature, and the visual arts, this study reveals the intimate connections between instrumental music and the scientific and artisanal tools that served to mediate between individuals and the world around them.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aInstrumental musiczItalyy17th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aMusiczItalyy17th centuryxHistory and criticism. 7aMUSIC / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package 2014-2016z978311070422808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package 2016z978311068860308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226319582423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226319582.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  a978-3-11-068860-3  UChP eBook-Package 2016b2016  a978-3-11-070422-8  UChP eBook-Package 2014-2016c2014d2016  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles